I had the same issue. My workaround was to call a function to check, within the `SKTouchAction.Moved` switch case, if a move is actually a tap:
```
private bool CheckIsTap(SKPoint pt)
{
    return _startMovePoint != null 
       && _startMoveTime != null 
       && SKPoint.Distance(pt, _startMovePoint) < 20 
       && (DateTime.Now - _startMoveTime).TotalMilliseconds < 100;
}
```
`_startMovePoint ` and `_startMoveTime` being the location and time of the tap event triggered just before the move event.
